        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria — micromotion and interface stress as fixation surrogates",
        "description": "Primary QoI (peak tibial tray micromotion) must be traceable to the clinical failure mode (aseptic loosening) via a documented biological rationale citing peer-reviewed literature (Pilliar 1986 threshold, Jasty 1997 histology). Secondary QoI (interface shear stress) must be linked to the same failure pathway."
      },
      "rationale": "Peak micromotion selected as primary QoI per Pilliar (1986) threshold of 150 µm for bone ingrowth inhibition. Interface shear stress linked to fibrous tissue formation pathway (Jasty 1997). Both QoIs directly traceable to the regulatory submission endpoint (aseptic loosening rate). Traceability matrix documented in QoI Relevance Report QR-TKA-2025-01."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-tka-validation-relevance",
